<Worksheet><Version major="6" minor="0"/><View-Properties><Zoom percentage="100"/></View-Properties><Styles><Layout alignment="centred" bullet="none" name="Author" spaceabove="8.0" spacebelow="8.0"/><Layout alignment="left" bullet="none" name="Heading 1" spaceabove="8.0" spacebelow="4.0"/><Layout alignment="left" bullet="none" firstindent="0.0" leftmargin="0.0" linebreak="space" name="Normal" rightmargin="0.0" spaceabove="0.0" spacebelow="0.0"/><Layout alignment="centred" bullet="none" name="Title" spaceabove="12.0" spacebelow="12.0"/><Font background="[0,0,0]" bold="false" family="Lucida Bright" foreground="[0,0,0]" italic="false" name="Text" opaque="false" size="12" underline="false"/><Font background="[0,0,0]" family="Lucida Bright" name="Author" opaque="false" size="12"/><Font background="[0,0,0]" bold="true" family="Serif" name="Heading 1" opaque="false" size="18"/><Font background="[0,0,0]" bold="true" executable="true" family="Monospaced" foreground="[255,0,0]" name="Maple Input" opaque="false" size="12"/><Font background="[0,0,0]" bold="true" family="Lucida Bright" name="Title" opaque="false" size="18" underline="true"/><Font background="[0,0,0]" executable="false" family="Lucida Bright" foreground="[0,0,0]" name="2D Math" opaque="false" size="12"/></Styles><Group><Input><Text-field firstindent="0.0" layout="Title" leftmargin="0.0" linebreak="space" rightmargin="0.0" style="Title"><Font executable="false" foreground="[0,0,0]" italic="false">Math243: Maple problem set #2.</Font></Text-field><Text-field firstindent="0.0" layout="Author" leftmargin="0.0" linebreak="space" rightmargin="0.0" style="Author"><Font bold="true" executable="false" foreground="[0,0,0]" italic="false" underline="true">Your name goes here.</Font></Text-field><Text-field firstindent="0.0" layout="Author" leftmargin="0.0" linebreak="space" rightmargin="0.0" style="Author">Due: 22 October 2003</Text-field><Text-field alignment="left" bullet="none" firstindent="0.0" layout="default" leftmargin="0.0" linebreak="space" rightmargin="0.0" spaceabove="8.0" spacebelow="8.0" style="default"><Font executable="false" style="Text">All solutions must be found using Maple.</Font></Text-field><Text-field alignment="left" bullet="none" firstindent="0.0" layout="default" leftmargin="0.0" linebreak="space" rightmargin="0.0" spaceabove="8.0" spacebelow="8.0" style="default"><Font background="[0,0,0]" family="Lucida Bright">This exercise uses<Font background="[0,0,0]" bold="true" family="Lucida Bright"> <Font background="[0,0,0]" bold="true" family="Lucida Bright">p<Font background="[0,0,0]" bold="true" family="Lucida Bright">lot3d<Font background="[0,0,0]" bold="true" family="Lucida Bright">, s<Font background="[0,0,0]" bold="true" family="Lucida Bright">phereplot<Font background="[0,0,0]" bold="true" family="Lucida Bright">, spacecurve, implicitplot3d</Font></Font></Font></Font></Font></Font><Font background="[0,0,0]" family="Lucida Bright">.</Font></Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Section collapsed="true"><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 1" style="Heading 1">First things first.</Text-field></Title><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Text">The first thing you should do with Maple is load in the packages you will need.  There's no harm in being careful and loading in things that you think you might need, even if you do not use them.</Text-field><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">with(LinearAlgebra):</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">with(plots):</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"/></Input></Group></Section><Text-field/><Text-field/><Section collapsed="true"><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 1" style="Heading 1">Problems.</Text-field></Title><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Text">1.  Plot the sphere <Equation input-equation="x^2+y^2+z^2 = 1" style="2D Math">NiMvLCgqJEkieEc2IiIiIyIiIiokSSJ5R0YnRihGKSokSSJ6R0YnRihGKUYp</Equation> using plot3d (patching together to branches of square root) and sphereplot.  Compare your results.</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"/></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Text">2.  Use Maple to determine how many times the helix <Equation input-equation="&lt;cos(t),sin(t),t&gt;" style="2D Math">NiMtSSQ8LD5HNiI2JC1JJGNvc0dGJTYjSSJ0R0YlNiQtSSRzaW5HRiVGKUYq</Equation> crosses the plane <Equation input-equation="10*x + 10*y + z = 1" style="2D Math">NiMvLCgqJiIjNSIiIkkieEc2IkYnRicqJkYmRidJInlHRilGJ0YnSSJ6R0YpRidGJw==</Equation>
.</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"/></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Text">3. Consider the surface <Equation input-equation="(x^2/4)+y^2+z^2-5*x-10*y+16*z+113 = 0" style="2D Math">NiMvLDAqJkkieEc2IiIiIyIiJSEiIiIiIiokSSJ5R0YnRihGKyokSSJ6R0YnRihGKyomIiImRitGJkYrRioqJiIjNUYrRi1GK0YqKiYiIztGK0YvRitGKyIkOCJGKyIiIQ==</Equation>.  Anticipate what the surface is and where it is located (e.g. "A sphere of radius ... centered at ...").  Use this information to plot it using implicitplot3d.</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"/></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Text"><Font executable="false">4.  Consider the curves r[1](t) = &lt;cos(2*t),sin(2*t),cos(3*t)&gt; and r[2](t) = &lt;cos(2*t),sin(2*t),cos(Pi*t)&gt;.  Plot them in the parameter ranges </Font><Equation input-equation="[0, Pi]" style="2D Math">NiM3JCIiIUkjUGlHSSpwcm90ZWN0ZWRHRiY=</Equation><Font executable="false">, </Font><Equation input-equation="[0,2*Pi]" style="2D Math">NiM3JCIiISomIiIjIiIiSSNQaUdJKnByb3RlY3RlZEdGKUYn</Equation><Font executable="false"> and </Font><Equation input-equation="[0,4*Pi]" style="2D Math">NiM3JCIiISomIiIlIiIiSSNQaUdJKnByb3RlY3RlZEdGKUYn</Equation><Font executable="false">.  Which curve repeats itself and which does not?  You may need to set numpoints to get clean renderings.  Feel free to experiment with other parameter ranges to gain intuition on the problem.  Explain this mathematically by studying the periods of each of the components.</Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"/></Input></Group></Section><Text-field/><Text-field/><Text-field/><Text-field/></Worksheet>